And I can assure you, my graduation as a professional counsellor with qualifications for the ACA (Australian counselling association), were the only in depth training I had to provide one on one mental health treatment. Every other course like my psych (Hons) SW, etc did not. 1/ https://t.co/7ygavsYauN
(Except psychiatry)

One of the reason social workers can be employed in these roles is because they have a license to adjacent roles, while the Australian counselling association cannot get Medicare rebates for their graduates.
I know this, because I have ALL the qualifications talked about above.

A skill set that takes years to hone and do well. Under the watchful eye of crucial supervision and feedback. The system is stretched and I worry about people sitting in roles and providing sub optimal care that actually makes things worse.

Places are now employing social workers as well as trained psychologists or clinical psychologists, but social workers often don’t have the depth of training to simply sit in a therapeutic role. They can case manage, but CBT and other important interventions are a skill set.

GPs are now prescribing mental health meds, and they often don’t understand how to recognise mental health issues and often take clients word for it. There’s not enough psychiatrists or psychologists.
